<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?><feed xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" ><generator uri="https://jekyllrb.com/" version="3.9.0">Jekyll</generator><link href="http://localhost:4000/feed.xml" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /><link href="http://localhost:4000/" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><updated>2021-08-15T16:06:24+10:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/feed.xml</id><title type="html">Conan cookery</title><subtitle>GF</subtitle><author><name>Conan Liu</name></author><entry><title type="html">Integrating Github with RStudio project</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/blog-ds-and-coding/ds/2021/07/24/Github-integration-with-R.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Integrating Github with RStudio project" /><published>2021-07-24T23:28:16+10:00</published><updated>2021-07-24T23:28:16+10:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/blog-ds-and-coding/ds/2021/07/24/Github-integration-with-R</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/blog-ds-and-coding/ds/2021/07/24/Github-integration-with-R.html">&lt;h1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Why?&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;p&gt;By integrating an RStudio project with Github, you can directly push changes using Git. This is extremely convenient and is actually what I used to build a website for my club, completely within R itself. And, to my observation, you can create a whole project, sync it to a new repo and when you commit+push all your new files, you may upload more than 100 files at once.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Step 1: create a new Github repository&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Go create a new repository. The &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;readme.md&lt;/code&gt; file is optional.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Step 2: enable Git in RStudio&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Open your project in RStudio and follow Tools -&amp;gt; Version Control -&amp;gt; Project Setup.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Click on the SVN/Git tab. Select Git as the version control system. It will ask you to initialise a new Git repo and restart RStudio.&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;After Rstudio reopens, confirm that there is a Git tab in the &lt;b&gt;environment&lt;b&gt; (where you view all your objects) pane (top right by default).&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
  &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Step 3: synchronise with a Github repository&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In RStudio, click on the terminal tab and start a new terminal session. Then enter:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-terminal&quot; data-lang=&quot;terminal&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;go&quot;&gt;cd&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This sets your terminal directory to home default. Then add next locations step wise. For me, I had my project on my desktop, and its name was “club”. So, I would enter:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-terminal&quot; data-lang=&quot;terminal&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;go&quot;&gt;cd Desktop&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;And then&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-terminal&quot; data-lang=&quot;terminal&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;go&quot;&gt;cd Desktop/club&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Next, set an origin:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-terminal&quot; data-lang=&quot;terminal&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;go&quot;&gt;git remote add origin https://github.com/yourUSERname/REPOname.git&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If you added optional files into your repo, such as the &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;.gitignore&lt;/code&gt;, &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;readme.md&lt;/code&gt; or &lt;code class=&quot;language-plaintext highlighter-rouge&quot;&gt;license.md&lt;/code&gt; file, enter&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-terminal&quot; data-lang=&quot;terminal&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;go&quot;&gt;git pull origin master&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To pull them from the otherwise empty repository. If you didn’t add any files, no need for this step.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Finally, enter&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;figure class=&quot;highlight&quot;&gt;&lt;pre&gt;&lt;code class=&quot;language-terminal&quot; data-lang=&quot;terminal&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;go&quot;&gt;git push -u origin master&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/figure&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Now, you should be ready to commit files to the repository. Along the way you may have needed to sign in to your Github account and entered some keychains if on a Mac.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h1&gt;&lt;b&gt;Step 4: push files to Github from RStudio&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the environment pane, click on the Git tab and then click Commit. This will open a window where you can track files you made changes to. Tick all boxes for files you want to push. If you are using Github to build a website, and you have lots of files changing at once after building it to see how it looks, you can tick one box, go CMD+A and tick all of them. Write a commit message in the adjacent field and then click an up arrow to push.&lt;/p&gt;</content><author><name>Conan Liu</name></author><category term="blog-ds-and-coding" /><category term="ds" /><summary type="html">Why?</summary></entry><entry><title type="html">Report</title><link href="http://localhost:4000/blog-academic/academic/2021/04/11/fourier.html" rel="alternate" type="text/html" title="Report" /><published>2021-04-11T23:28:16+10:00</published><updated>2021-04-11T23:28:16+10:00</updated><id>http://localhost:4000/blog-academic/academic/2021/04/11/fourier</id><content type="html" xml:base="http://localhost:4000/blog-academic/academic/2021/04/11/fourier.html">&lt;p&gt;Fourier Transform report:&lt;/p&gt;

